That's just plain silly.  Wizards get one common nuke at lvl 60--it does 1.2k damage.  The other three:  SS, EER, and GSS are all <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   rare</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  SS seems almost non-existent some times, and EER/GSS well they drop frequently from the mob who's loot table they are on, those mobs aren't exactly a cackewalk for 99% of the guilds out there!  How many Emp-capable guilds are there on your server?  Two to four maybe, at best?  Of those, how many Wizards do they have between them, say an average of 5 each, so up to 20 lvl 60 Wizards...  Now, Emp is what, a one week spawn?  So that's 20 weeks before any guild will even be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>   thinking</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about selling GSS, and then it's going to be 250-1000k to buy it.<br>
<br>
Now you're saying it's just fine for a Mage to get a 2k nuke as soon as they ding 61, while most Wizards are still stuck with a 1.2k (and a 13 second recast)?  I'm assuming FoT will be buyable, or at least a common drop, since all previous bolts have been purchasable from vendor.<br>
<br>
Even if all lvl 60 Wizards do have GSS, why is it OK for Magi to have a spell one level after Wizards that is essentially the same damage and ratio?  Magi cry a river when Druids get similar nukes, but when it's a Mage compared to a Wizard, it's OK?<br>
<br>
Actually a few more points.  I cannot begin to describe how mindboggling it is that the very same Magi who complain the loudest about Druids getting within one mile of their nuking ability will turn around and adamently defend FoT.  The only real defense I see people trying to put up is the LoS issue.  That's total crap and you all know it.  Yes, bolts <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> can</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be a PitA to aim, but it's not impossible to overcome.  Our last time up in Hate we had 35 toons and I used Scars of Sigil almost exclusively.  If I were trying to use FoT on a raid, I would load SoS and use it for aiming, then unload FoT after I got a SoS to hit.  Really, if you play with LoS for a few casts you quickly get the hang of it and it's not a problem.  Worst comes to worst, you can always blast away from melee range.<br>
<br>
Second for Raz:  I think there are two reasons why you didn't get a big reaction out of the Graffe's bunch: a.) they see it as sort of just compensation, but heavily dependent on b.) no one seriously thinks the spell will go live with it's current data.  Everyone is pretty much ignoring it, much like I considered the original manacost of Insanity.  It's just <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> too</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> good, there's no way it will go live like that. <p><CENTER>
